# C++ Doxygen Documentation Style Rules

These rules define the standard Doxygen documentation style for C++ code.


## Best Practices
1. Use complete sentences ending with periods
2. Be concise but descriptive in @brief tags
3. Provide detailed explanations in @details when necessary
4. Document all parameters, even if their purpose seems obvious
5. Document exceptions that may be thrown
6. Include units for numerical parameters/returns where applicable
7. Use @note for important additional information
8. Use @warning for potential pitfalls or dangerous usage
9. Keep documentation up to date with code changes
10. Use consistent terminology throughout documentation

## Code Preservation
1. Do not change any code style when adding documentation
2. Never modify or refactor the code when adding documentation
3. Never add additional code when adding documentation
4. Never remove any existing code when adding documentation
5. Do not fix any code issues when adding documentation
6. Documentation should describe the code as-is, not as it could/should be
7. Keep all existing code structure, formatting, and logic intact
8. Focus solely on adding descriptive comments and documentation

## Formatting Guidelines
1. Use proper grammar and punctuation
2. Align asterisks in multi-line comments
3. Use empty lines to separate logical sections in detailed descriptions
4. Maintain consistent indentation
5. Break long lines at 100 characters
6. Use markdown formatting in detailed descriptions when helpful

## Special Tags Reference
- @brief - Short description
- @details - Detailed description
- @param - Parameter description
- @tparam - Template parameter description
- @return - Return value description
- @throws - Exception description
- @pre - Precondition
- @post - Postcondition
- @note - Additional notes
- @warning - Warnings
- @see - References to other elements
- @since - Version information
- @deprecated - Deprecation notice 

## Class Documentation
Classes should be documented with a comprehensive header:
```cpp
/**
 * @class ClassName
 * @brief Brief description of the class
 * @details 
 * Detailed description of the class, its purpose, and any important notes.
 * Multiple paragraphs are allowed.
 * 
 * @note Important notes about the class
 * @warning Any warnings about class usage
 */
```

## Function Documentation
Functions should be documented with parameters, return values, and exceptions:
```cpp
/**
 * @brief Brief description of what the function does
 * @details 
 * Detailed description of the function's behavior
 * 
 * @param[in] paramName Description of input parameter
 * @param[out] paramName Description of output parameter
 * @param[in,out] paramName Description of parameter that's both input and output
 * 
 * @return Description of return value
 * 
 * @throws ExceptionType Description of when/why exception is thrown
 * 
 * @pre Preconditions that must be met
 * @post Postconditions that are guaranteed
 * 
 * @note Any additional notes
 * @warning Any warnings about function usage
 */
```

## Member Variable Documentation
Member variables should be documented concisely:
```cpp
/**
 * @brief Brief description of the member variable
 * @details Detailed description if necessary
 */
```

## Enum Documentation
Enums should be documented with descriptions for both the enum and its values:
```cpp
/**
 * @brief Brief description of the enum
 * @details Detailed description of the enum's purpose
 */
enum class EnumName {
    /**
     * @brief Description of first enum value
     */
    VALUE_ONE,
    
    /**
     * @brief Description of second enum value
     */
    VALUE_TWO
};
```

## Template Parameter Documentation
Template parameters should be documented:
```cpp
/**
 * @brief Brief description of the template class/function
 * 
 * @tparam T Description of template parameter T
 * @tparam N Description of template parameter N
 */
```

## Groups and Modules
Use groups to organize related elements:
```cpp
/**
 * @defgroup group_name Group Title
 * @{
 */

// ... documented elements ...

/**
 * @}
 */
```
